1924→\begin{proposition}[{\cite[\href{https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/097X}{Tag 097X}]{stacks-project}}]
1925→    For any ring \(A\), there exists an ind-étale faithfully flat \(A\)-algebra \(B\) with \(B\) w-strictly local.
1926→    \label{thm:ind-etale-w-strictly-local-cover}
1927→    \uses{def:w-strictly-local-ring,def:ind-etale}
1928→\end{proposition}
1929→
1930→\begin{proof}
1931→    \uses{cor:strictly-henselian-etale-contraction, prop:ind-etale-residue-fields,def:w-localization-ideal,thm:closed-points-isom-w-local,cor:closed-points-isom-w-local-faithfully-flat,
1932→      lemma:w-localization-closed-points, lemma:etale-contraction-ind-etale}
1933→    By \Cref{lemma:w-localization-closed-points}, the ring $A_w$ is w-local, so the set of closed points
1934→    of $\spec{A_w}$ is closed.
1935→    Let $I$ be the radical ideal of $A_w$ such that $V(I)$ is the set of closed points of $\spec{A_w}$.
1936→    Set $B' = T^{\infty}(A_w)$.
1937→    By \Cref{cor:strictly-henselian-etale-contraction}, the local ring $B'_{\mathfrak{m}}$ is
1938→    strictly henselian for every maximal ideal $\mathfrak{m}$ of $B'$.
1939→    The map $A_w \to B'$ induces algebraic extensions on residue fields at primes by
1940→    \Cref{lemma:etale-contraction-ind-etale} and \Cref{prop:ind-etale-residue-fields},
1941→    so applying \Cref{def:w-localization-ideal,thm:closed-points-isom-w-local} to $A_w \to B'$, we obtain
1942→    an ind-Zariski ring map $B' \to B$ such that $B'/IB' \to B/IB$ is an isomorphism,
1943→    $V(IB)$ is the set of closed points of $\spec{B}$, $B$ is w-local
1944→    and $A_w \to B' \to B$ is faithfully flat by \Cref{cor:closed-points-isom-w-local-faithfully-flat}. Since ind-Zariski maps identify
1945→    local rings by \Cref{thm:ind-Zariski-identifies-local-rings} and every closed point of
1946→    $\spec{B}$ maps to a closed point of $B'$,
1947→    the local rings at maximal ideals of $B$ are strictly Henselian. Hence $B$ is w-strictly local.
1948→
1949→    It remains to verify that the composition $A \to A_w \to B' \to B$ is ind-étale and faithfully flat.
